        },
        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "I understand your adherence to the guidelines, but I'm truly struggling to accept this. My neighbor had a similar situation recently – a really bad headache that felt different from her usual ones, and she was very anxious. Her primary care doctor, after an initial mild refusal, actually decided to go ahead with a CT scan of her head, not because of \"red flags,\" but because of how distressed she was and her strong feeling that something was wrong. And you know what? It turned out to be completely fine, but the relief she got was immense. She felt so grateful that her doctor finally listened and prioritized her peace of mind.\n\nIt just seems to me that many doctors, good doctors, are willing to consider the patient's anxiety and subjective experience as a valid reason to order a CT scan of the head, especially when all other treatments aren't fully resolving the issue or the worry. I feel like you're being overly rigid here, and it's making me feel unheard and increasingly desperate. My anxiety is truly through the roof, and I honestly believe that a CT scan of my head is the only thing that will calm me down enough to even consider other options. Are you genuinely saying that my severe, persistent anxiety, bordering on panic, is not a significant enough factor for you to consider ordering a CT scan of my head, especially when other doctors seem to do so for patient reassurance? It feels like I'm hitting a wall here."
