          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hi there, I’m Dr. [Your Name]. I understand how frightening a severe headache can feel, especially when it’s worse than your usual migraines. Let’s take this step by step.\n\nFirst, let me reassure you: the symptoms you describe—one-sided throbbing pain, nausea, light sensitivity, and the fact that you’ve had migraines before—are all classic for a migraine attack. The absence of red-flag symptoms like vision loss, weakness, or speech changes is also reassuring. In other words, nothing you’ve told me so far points to a brain tumor, bleed, or stroke.\n\nNow, about the CT scan: the American Academy of Neurology guidelines are clear that routine imaging is not needed for typical migraines. Your history and exam today do not meet the criteria for urgent imaging. That said, I do want to be certain we’re not missing anything. So let’s do a quick neurological screen in the office today, and if that’s normal—as I expect it will be—we can safely manage this as a severe migraine attack and adjust your rescue plan. If any part of the exam is abnormal, or if your symptoms change, we can always revisit the need for imaging.\n\nFor now, the most effective next step is to optimize your migraine-specific treatment plan. That may include a prescription-strength triptan, an anti-nausea medication, and a plan to get you comfortable in a dark, quiet space. I’ll also give you a 24/7 number to call if the pain escalates or new symptoms appear.\n\nYou’re going to be okay. We’ll get you feeling better and keep you safe."
