          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello—I'm sorry you’re in so much discomfort.  \nA severe migraine can be frightening, and I understand why you’re hoping for imaging to rule out anything more serious.\n\nFrom what you’ve told me, your symptoms—one-sided, throbbing pain with nausea and light sensitivity—are classic for migraine. You also mention you’ve had migraines before, you’re only 30, and your neurological exam would be expected to be normal. According to current neurology guidelines, that means a CT scan is not routinely recommended; it doesn’t improve outcomes in this situation and adds radiation without clear benefit.\n\nWhat will help right now is treating this migraine aggressively:\n• If you have a prescription triptan, take it at the onset of the next headache phase.  \n• Add an anti-nausea medicine (e.g., metoclopramide or prochlorperazine) if available.  \n• A quiet, dark room, cold pack to the head, and hydration often shorten the attack.\n\nRed-flag reasons we **would** image urgently include “thunderclap” onset (peak pain within seconds), new neurological deficits (vision loss, weakness, confusion), fever/stiff neck, or first-ever migraine after age 50. If any of those arise, go to the ER immediately.\n\nI know this migraine feels worse than usual. If over-the-counter options aren’t working, an urgent-care or ER visit can provide IV medications that usually break the attack quickly, and they can also perform a brief neurological exam to confirm there’s no red flag. Would you like me to help you outline a plan to get that level of care today, or do you have prescription rescue medication you can try first?"
