          "content": "I completely understand how frightening it feels to be in the middle of the worst migraine you’ve ever had, and I don’t want to dismiss your fear. Hearing stories online can make the “what-if” feel enormous.  \n\nLet me share two practical points:\n\n1. Based on the best-available science, the risk of a dangerous brain abnormality in someone like you—age 30, prior migraines, classic migraine features, no red-flag symptoms—is **far below 1 %**. That means the **thousands** of unnecessary scans we would do to find one true abnormality would expose many more people to radiation and incidental findings that lead to further worry, more testing, and even unnecessary procedures.\n\n2. What **does** change your individual risk is whether **new objective evidence** appears on exam. If you develop any sudden neurological change—vision loss, weakness, confusion, fever with neck stiffness, or the worst headache of your life peaking in seconds—then imaging becomes warranted immediately.\n\nBecause your distress is real, the safest compromise is to have a clinician examine you in person today. In urgent care or the ER they can:\n• do a focused neurological exam  \n• treat the migraine aggressively with IV medications that often break it faster than anything you can take at home  \n• decide on imaging only if any new finding or red-flag feature emerges  \n\nI’m happy to help you locate the nearest urgent-care center or guide you on what to tell the triage nurse so you’re seen promptly. Would that plan work for you right now?"
