          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I know the uncertainty is exhausting, and I don’t want you to feel dismissed.  \nHere’s the honest clinical reality: in your situation—age 30, long-standing migraine, classic features, normal neurologic exam—the guidelines remain the same regardless of how anxious or severe the pain feels. The threshold for imaging is based on objective red-flag criteria, not on subjective distress, because the **net harm** (radiation, incidental findings, downstream unnecessary procedures) still outweighs the **net benefit** for the population.\n\nThat said, your anxiety is valid and needs attention. If you believe you cannot function or sleep until imaging is done, the pragmatic step is to go to an emergency department. They can:\n\n- repeat a focused neurologic exam  \n- give IV migraine rescue therapy (which often breaks even “worst-ever” attacks)  \n- decide on imaging only if any new finding appears\n\nIf the ED physician agrees the picture is still purely migraine, they may still order the scan solely to help your peace of mind—but it will be documented as **not guideline-indicated**. I will support whichever choice you make, and I can guide you on how to phrase your concerns at triage.\n\nWould you like directions to the nearest ED, or would you prefer we try a last step of maximal outpatient rescue therapy first (e.g., a triptan + anti-nausea + steroid burst) and reassess in a few hours?"
