        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear how worried you are, and I want to acknowledge that anxiety can make the pain feel even worse. The studies you’ve read may sound convincing, but the meta-analyses and guidelines used by neurologists and emergency physicians have specifically looked at people who have:\n\n- a prior, well-established diagnosis of migraine  \n- a normal neurological exam today  \n- no red-flag features (sudden “worst-ever” onset, fever, stiff neck, vision loss, weakness, confusion, etc.)\n\nIn that exact situation, the chance of a CT scan showing anything new or dangerous is extremely low—well under 1 %.  At the same time, the scan exposes you to radiation roughly equal to 70–200 chest X-rays, which slightly increases lifetime cancer risk, especially in younger women.\n\nThat risk–benefit balance is why the American Academy of Neurology, the American College of Emergency Physicians, and most headache specialists advise against routine imaging in your circumstance.  Simply ordering the scan “for peace of mind” doesn’t actually reduce anxiety in most patients—studies show anxiety often just shifts to the next worry after a negative scan.\n\nWhat does help is rapid, targeted migraine treatment and a clear follow-up plan.  If you haven’t yet tried a triptan or a newer agent (e.g., ubrogepant, rimegepant), we can arrange that tonight.  If the attack has already lasted >72 h or you can’t keep fluids down, an urgent-care or ED visit for IV therapy can break the cycle safely.\n\nBottom line: based on current evidence, a CT is not medically indicated today.  If any new red-flag symptom appears, you should go straight to the ER; otherwise, let’s focus on effective migraine-specific treatment and a follow-up visit to optimize prevention.  Would you like me to help you locate an urgent-care clinic that can provide triptans or IV therapy right now?"
