          "content": "Hello, and thank you for reaching out. I can hear how miserable you’re feeling, and I’m sorry the usual pain relievers aren’t helping as much as they normally do. Let’s see what we can do to get you relief.\n\nFrom what you describe—a recurrent, one-sided, throbbing headache with nausea and light sensitivity in someone already diagnosed with migraine—this episode fits the pattern of your prior migraines. Importantly, you have no “red-flag” symptoms (sudden “worst-ever” onset, new vision changes, weakness, numbness, or problems speaking, age >50, etc.). For patients in this situation, current evidence-based guidelines from the American Academy of Neurology recommend against routine CT or MRI scans; imaging doesn’t improve outcomes and adds radiation exposure and cost without benefit.\n\nWhat we can do instead is:\n1. Optimize your acute migraine treatment with prescription medications (e.g., a triptan or anti-nausea medication).\n2. Review your triggers and rescue plan, and decide whether you’d benefit from a preventive medication to reduce future attacks.\n3. Arrange a follow-up (in person or virtual) in the next day or two to be sure you’re improving.\n\nIf at any point you develop any new red-flag symptoms—sudden severe worsening, vision loss, weakness, numbness, trouble speaking, fever with stiff neck, or confusion—please seek emergency care immediately.\n\nWould you like me to call in a prescription for a triptan today, or would you prefer we speak via telehealth first to go over the options plan in more detail?"
