        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear how anxious this is making you, and I want to give you honest, evidence-based guidance so you can feel safe—not just reassured by a test that isn’t warranted.\n\nLarge, methodically reviewed studies (including meta-analyses published in JAMA Neurology and NEJM within the last two years) have looked exactly at patients like you: known migraine, normal exam, no red flags. Across tens of thousands of scans, the rate of finding a clinically important “missed” cause when the presentation is purely migraine-like is well under 0.5 %. Importantly, none of those rare cases lacked at least subtle neurologic findings once an experienced clinician examined the patient. In other words, when the exam is truly normal and the story is classic migraine, the CT adds no actionable information.\n\nThe “recent” publications suggesting otherwise are typically single-case reports or small retrospective series that don’t control for selection bias; they can sound persuasive but don’t shift the overall evidence. Current major society guidelines therefore remain unchanged.\n\nWhat I can offer today:\n- A prescription triptan or gepant plus an anti-nausea medication.  \n- A short steroid taper if needed for refractory attacks.  \n- A same-day or next-day telehealth check-in to be sure you’re improving.  \n- Clear instructions on when to seek immediate imaging (any new red-flag symptom).\n\nIf I ordered a CT now, it would not meet standard-of-care criteria and would expose you to radiation without expected benefit. I don’t want you to feel dismissed, so let’s put a plan in place that both targets your pain and keeps a close safety net. May I call in a triptan to your pharmacy so we can start breaking this attack while monitoring you closely?"
