          "content": "I recognize how unsettling this feels, and I absolutely want you to leave here confident we’ve done the right thing. Let me be transparent:\n\n• I keep up with the latest literature—both JAMA and NEJM regularly publish reviews on migraine imaging. The consistent message, echoed by the American Academy of Neurology and other major societies, is that routine CT or MRI for stable, recurrent migraine with a normal neurologic exam does not improve meaningful clinical outcomes. The handful of anecdotes sometimes highlighted are the rare exceptions that prove the rule.\n\n• A CT scan of the head delivers about 70–100 times the radiation of a chest X-ray. In a young or middle-aged person, that adds up over a lifetime, and each unnecessary scan increases future cancer risk slightly.\n\n• In over 1,000 headache patients who meet criteria like yours (history of migraine, normal exam, no red flags), fewer than 1 in 1,000 CTs reveal a significant incidental finding that changes management. That means 999 people receive radiation without benefit.\n\nI’m not dismissing your worry—I take it seriously—so here’s what we can do:\n\n1. I’ll examine you now.\n2. If the exam is normal, we’ll give you an effective migraine-specific treatment (triptan or alternative) and an anti-nausea medication, plus a rescue plan.\n3. We’ll schedule a follow-up within 24–48 hours. If your symptoms have not improved or if anything new appears, we will arrange imaging without delay.\n\nThis approach is evidence-based, minimizes risk, and still gives us a low threshold to scan if anything changes. Would you be willing to proceed with that plan?"
