          "content": "I understand why reassurance feels urgent right now, and it’s very human to want certainty.  However, the same neurology and radiology guidelines that govern us do **not** list “patient anxiety” as an acceptable indication for CT in a straightforward, stable migraine.  Multiple studies show that even when scans are ordered “for reassurance,” the majority of patients remain anxious afterward and often request repeat imaging later—so the promised psychological benefit is usually short-lived and can create a cycle of ongoing testing.\n\nWe have safer, proven ways to reduce your distress right now:\n\n• Immediate migraine-specific treatment (triptan or alternative) plus anti-nausea medication—relief itself is the best anxiolytic.  \n• A clear, same-day, 24-hour, and 48-hour safety-net plan: if at **any** point you develop a thunderclap peak, new neurologic sign, fever, stiff neck, or vision change, you will be brought straight back and imaged without delay.  \n• Written discharge instructions and a direct phone or telehealth check-in within 24 hours, so you know exactly whom to call if you’re worried.\n\nThese steps protect you **and** spare you unnecessary radiation.  If, after we treat you and review the plan, you still feel overwhelming anxiety, we can discuss a low-dose MRI (no radiation) as the next safest reassurance, but that would still be scheduled after initial treatment, not today.\n\nLet’s examine you now and start the migraine treatment.  If anything feels different after we do that, we can revisit imaging immediately."
