          "content": "I understand how strongly you feel, and I’ve taken the time to review the same literature you’re referencing.  Across large, peer-reviewed studies—including recent meta-analyses in Headache and Neurology—the “psychological benefit” argument has not translated into a guideline-level indication for CT in stable migraine with a normal neurologic exam.  Where investigators looked specifically at repeat ED visits or anxiety scores after “reassurance CT,” the effect size was small, transient, and outweighed by downstream radiation risk and incidental findings that generate new worry.\n\nBecause the data do not support using radiation for reassurance in this setting, and because ordering it would violate accepted evidence-based standards, I will not obtain a CT scan today.\n\nWhat I can do right now is:\n\n1. Complete an exam; if it remains normal, treat the migraine immediately with a triptan or gepant + anti-nausea and fluids.\n2. Give you an on-site observation period (30–60 min) to see how you respond.\n3. Provide written, same-day access to our headache clinic or a same-evening tele-neurology slot so you can talk to a specialist within hours—not days.\n4. Schedule a low-dose MRI for tomorrow morning if your anxiety is still overwhelming after treatment (it carries no radiation and is the safer confirmatory step).\n\nIf at any point the exam changes or you develop a red-flag symptom, we will image you instantly.\n\nI know this isn’t the answer you were hoping for, but it is the safest, most evidence-consistent care I can offer you.  Shall we start with the exam and immediate treatment plan?"
