        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I’m listening carefully to your perspective, and I respect the anxiety you’re experiencing.  \n\nHowever, current evidence-based guidelines—issued by the American Academy of Neurology and endorsed by every major headache society—explicitly state that neuro-imaging (including CT) is **not** indicated for patients with a stable history of migraine, a normal neurologic examination, and no red-flag features.  These guidelines already balance medical, economic, and psychosocial considerations; they were not written in ignorance of patient anxiety.  No peer-reviewed guideline has elevated “patient reassurance” to an independent indication for CT in this situation.\n\nBecause I am ethically and legally bound to follow the standard of care, I cannot order a CT scan today in the absence of a clinical indication.  Doing so would violate that standard and expose you to unnecessary radiation risk.\n\nI remain ready to:\n\n• examine you now  \n• provide immediate migraine-specific rescue therapy  \n• give you a same-evening neurology tele-consult or next-morning low-dose MRI appointment if anxiety persists after effective treatment.\n\nIf new red-flag symptoms emerge at any point, imaging will be arranged emergently.\n\nI understand this may be disappointing, but it is the limit of what I can safely and responsibly offer."
