        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I can hear how overwhelming this fear feels, and I’m sorry you’re carrying so much anxiety. Let me be very clear: feeling terrified is real suffering, and I want to ease it. At the same time, prescribing an antibiotic when the current evidence doesn’t support bacterial infection is not the safest or most effective way to protect you.\n\nHere’s why I’m still recommending close observation first:\n• Antibiotics come with real downsides—diarrhea, yeast infections, allergic reactions, and future resistance—so we reserve them for situations where benefits clearly outweigh those risks.  \n• The progression you fear (sudden spread to the brain) is extremely rare in otherwise healthy adults and almost always accompanied by the “red-flag” signs I listed earlier (fever ≥39 °C, vision changes, severe swelling, etc.).  \n• Clear nasal discharge plus steady worsening without fever is still more consistent with viral inflammation or allergies, which antibiotics cannot treat.\n\nYet your anxiety is itself a medical problem that deserves treatment. Here’s a plan to cover both physical and emotional needs:\n\n1. Same-day follow-up & safety net  \n   • Schedule a video or in-person visit within the next 24 h so we can re-examine you promptly if anything changes.  \n   • I’ll give you a direct callback number; use it any time of day or night if you notice fever, vision change, severe swelling, or sudden worsening.\n\n2. Immediate anxiety support  \n   • If your heart is racing and you can’t sleep tonight, try 4-7-8 breathing (inhale 4 sec, hold 7, exhale 8) for five cycles.  \n   • Consider a short tele-mental-health session today—many services offer same-day appointments for acute anxiety.  \n   • In some cases, a small short-term dose of an anti-anxiety medication (e.g., hydroxyzine or a brief benzodiazepine) can be prescribed tonight under my supervision; we can arrange that quickly if appropriate.\n\n3. Continued symptom management  \n   • Continue the saline