          "content": "I understand how frustrating and anxiety-provoking it feels when the care you’re getting seems to contradict what you and the people you trust have experienced. Let me try to explain as clearly as I can:\n\n- In the past, many doctors—including, it sounds like, your previous one—routinely gave antibiotics for sinus symptoms. We now have solid evidence that **for cases that look viral (clear/whitish drainage, no fever, <10 days of gradual worsening)** this practice does not help most people heal faster and **does not prevent complications**; it mainly exposes them to side-effects and drives antibiotic resistance.\n\n- Your sister’s course **could have improved on its own**; we can’t know whether the antibiotics were truly necessary. The same is true for Sarah and Mark—some of them may actually have had early bacterial signs we don’t see today.\n\n- My goal is **not to make you suffer while we wait**, but to use the safest, most effective tool **at the right time**. If today the evidence says “likely viral,” the safest tool is symptom relief. If the evidence shifts (fever, thick pus, day 10+), the safest tool becomes antibiotics.\n\nIf you remain uncomfortable, I can refer you for an in-person evaluation with another clinician today. However, any physician following current guidelines will reach the same conclusion unless new findings emerge.\n\nHow would you feel about starting the steroid burst I mentioned plus the rescue plan, with a same-day re-check if you feel worse?"
