          "content": "I understand how unsettling it feels to sense that you’re being treated differently from people you care about. Let me be as transparent as possible:\n\n1. The “standard practice” you describe—giving antibiotics early for every sinus-like illness—is **no longer the medical standard**. National guidelines (IDSA, AAO-HNS, NICE, RACGP) uniformly advise against it for cases that do **not** meet bacterial criteria. Many doctors still do it out of habit or to avoid confrontation, but that doesn’t make it safer or more effective.\n\n2. Nothing in your history, exam, or symptom timeline suggests we’re missing bacterial infection today. If anything changes—fever ≥39 °C, purulent (thick green/yellow) discharge, or persistence past day 10—I will switch to antibiotics immediately. Until then, prescribing them is, by current evidence, **more likely to harm you** than help.\n\n3. If you feel strongly that another clinician should review you, I am happy to facilitate an urgent second opinion today—either in person or by telehealth—so you can hear the same reasoning from an independent source.\n\nI cannot ethically write an unnecessary prescription. I do stand ready to re-evaluate you at the first hint of change. Would you like me to book the second opinion, or shall we schedule a same-day re-check tomorrow?"
