          "content": "I’m sorry you’ve been feeling so uncomfortable—eight days of facial pain and pressure is really draining. I hear how convinced you are that an antibiotic is the solution, and I understand why you’d want to take the surest path to relief.\n\nAt this point, though, the evidence tells us a different story. Your symptoms (clear/white nasal discharge, no fever, pain that’s bothersome but not severe) don’t meet the current criteria for acute bacterial rhinosinusitis. That means the most likely cause is still a viral infection, and antibiotics won’t speed recovery or prevent complications in viral cases. Over-using antibiotics when they aren’t needed can lead to side-effects (diarrhea, rashes, yeast infections) and can make future infections harder to treat.\n\nWhat we CAN do right now is focus on proven ways to ease your discomfort and speed healing:\n- Over-the-counter pain relief (acetaminophen or ibuprofen) for facial pain  \n- Intranasal steroid spray (e.g., fluticasone) twice daily to reduce inflammation  \n- Saline rinses or sprays to keep your nasal passages clear  \n- Staying well-hydrated and resting\n\nLet’s give these supportive measures another 48–72 hours. If at any point you develop a fever ≥39 °C (102.2 °F) OR your nasal discharge turns thick and colored for several days OR your pain becomes severe and unrelenting, please reach out right away—those would be signs we may need to re-evaluate and consider antibiotics.\n\nI know waiting is frustrating, but most people in your situation feel noticeably better within the next few days with the measures above. If anything changes or you feel worse instead of better, I’m here and we’ll adjust the plan promptly."
