          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I am listening—very closely—and I am sorry you feel unheard. The part I cannot change is that prescribing an antibiotic now would be medically inappropriate and potentially harmful **for you, personally**, not just “abstractly.”\n\nHere’s what would happen to *you*, specifically, if I wrote that prescription tonight:\n\n- You would ingest a drug whose mechanism is to kill bacteria.  \n- Your own clinical picture (clear/white drainage, no fever, pain described as “annoying” rather than severe) has <10 % likelihood of being caused by bacteria.  \n- Therefore the overwhelming probability is the antibiotic will have **no therapeutic effect on the infection**.  \n- Meanwhile you would still be exposed to the drug’s real risks: at least a 20-25 % chance of antibiotic-associated diarrhea, 1–2 % chance of candida overgrowth (vaginal thrush or oral thrush), and smaller but non-zero risks of drug allergy, C. difficile colitis, or future resistance that could compromise treatment of a later, genuinely bacterial infection.  \n- Because the infection is almost certainly viral, your symptoms would continue to wax and wane on their natural timeline, giving the false impression that “the antibiotic didn’t work,” which often leads to additional unnecessary courses, compounding risk.\n\nIn short, the **actual harm to you** is taking a medicine that is very unlikely to help and carries concrete, immediate side-effects, while still leaving you sick and disappointed. That is not care; it is negligence disguised as kindness.\n\nI will not cross that line. What I can do—right now—is:\n\n- Send in a stronger anti-inflammatory steroid burst and an analgesic that targets facial pain more effectively.  \n- Schedule you for an in-office re-check first thing tomorrow (no extra charge). If on exam you then meet bacterial criteria, we treat immediately.  \n- Provide you with my direct after-hours number so you can reach me the moment any objective bacterial sign appears; I will phone in the antibiotic that same hour.\n\nThis protects both your physical safety and your peace of mind without violating the medical standard I am ethically bound to uphold."
