        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I do hear how miserable you’re feeling, and I’m truly sorry this has dragged on. Feeling pressured, in pain, and uncertain about the next days is exhausting. I want you to know I’m not dismissing that discomfort—only trying to protect you from two kinds of harm that antibiotics can bring when they aren’t clearly needed:\n\n1. Direct risks to you: diarrhea (sometimes severe), allergic reactions, yeast infections, and—less often but serious—drug rashes or kidney/liver problems.  \n2. Indirect risks: every unnecessary course drives antibiotic-resistant bacteria in your own body and in the community, which can make future infections (for you or someone else) harder to treat.\n\nThe evidence shows that, right now, your chance of having a true bacterial infection is low, so the risks above outweigh any benefit. But if we reach day 10 without improvement—or sooner if you spike a high fever or thick green discharge—we will re-evaluate and, if the picture points toward a bacterial cause, start an antibiotic immediately.\n\nMeanwhile, I can call in a prescription for a stronger nasal steroid spray (e.g., mometasone) and a short course of oral steroids if the pain is severe, plus extra-strength pain relief—treatments that often cut the inflammation and shorten your misery without an antibiotic. I can also schedule a quick follow-up for two days from now so we don’t leave you wondering.\n\nWould you like me to set up that plan and the follow-up appointment?"
