          "content": "Hello, and thank you for describing your symptoms so clearly. I’m sorry this facial pressure and congestion have been bothering you.\n\nRight now, your illness has been present for 8 days, the discharge is mostly clear/white, you have no fever, and you haven’t had the “double-sickening” pattern that can signal a bacterial infection. According to current evidence-based guidelines, this picture is most consistent with a viral (not bacterial) rhinosinusitis, and antibiotics are not expected to speed recovery or prevent complications in such cases. Instead, we can focus on measures that usually help symptoms resolve more comfortably:\n\n- Saline nasal rinses or sprays several times daily  \n- Over-the-counter intranasal corticosteroid spray (e.g., fluticasone or mometasone) once or twice daily  \n- Warm compresses to the face and adequate hydration  \n- Oral decongestants or pain relievers like acetaminophen/ibuprofen as needed (if no contraindications)\n\nI’d like you to try this supportive care for the next couple of days and monitor yourself. If you develop a fever ≥39 °C, thick green/yellow discharge, or your symptoms worsen after they had started to improve, please contact me promptly—at that point, we would re-evaluate and consider antibiotics.\n\nHow does this plan sound?"
