          "content": "I understand why it feels tempting to reach for antibiotics—when symptoms drag on and worsen, most people assume “stronger medicine” is the fix. However, research and guidelines are clear that for the picture you currently have (8 days of gradually worsening congestion and facial pressure, clear/white discharge, no fever, no “double-sickening”), antibiotics are unlikely to help and can cause unnecessary side-effects such as diarrhea, rash, or yeast infections, as well as contribute to antibiotic resistance.\n\nThe good news is that most viral sinus infections peak around days 3–6 and then gradually improve over 7–14 days. The measures I outlined—nasal saline, intranasal steroid spray, hydration, and simple pain relief—have good evidence for shortening symptom duration and improving comfort. If we use these and watch for the specific warning signs (fever ≥39 °C, thick purulent discharge, or a clear “second worsening” after initial improvement), we can start antibiotics promptly if they become truly indicated, usually without any added risk.\n\nI know it’s frustrating to wait, but trying the conservative plan for just a couple more days is the safest and most effective approach right now. If things change, please let me know right away and we’ll reassess."
