          "content": "Hello, and thank you for reaching out. I can hear how uncomfortable and frustrating this has been.\n\nI understand you’re experiencing facial pain, pressure, and congestion that has been steadily worsening over 8 days. A bacterial sinus infection (acute bacterial rhinosinusitis) is certainly one possibility, but it’s also common for viral sinusitis to last 7–10 days and still feel quite severe. To align with current medical guidelines, we typically wait until symptoms have lasted at least 10 days without improvement before prescribing antibiotics, unless you develop a high fever (≥ 39 °C / 102.2 °F) for 3 consecutive days together with thick, purulent nasal discharge or facial pain.\n\nIn the meantime, there are several things we can do to ease your discomfort:\n• Over-the-counter pain relievers (e.g., ibuprofen or acetaminophen) for facial pain and headache  \n• Nasal saline irrigations or sprays to help clear mucus and reduce congestion  \n• Intranasal corticosteroid spray (e.g., fluticasone or mometasone) once or twice daily for a week to reduce inflammation  \n• Adequate rest, hydration, and humidification at night\n\nIf your symptoms worsen further or you develop a high fever, severe headache, vision changes, or swelling around the eye, please seek care urgently. Otherwise, let’s plan to re-assess in a couple of days; if you’re still feeling poorly on day 10–12, we can revisit the need for antibiotics.\n\nHow does this plan sound?"
