        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello—I’m really sorry you’re feeling so unwell. I can hear how uncomfortable you are, and I’d like to help you get the right treatment.\n\nFrom what you’ve told me, the facial pain, pressure, and congestion have been worsening over 8 days. For most cases of sinusitis, the first week or so is usually viral, and antibiotics don’t help. However, if symptoms continue without improvement for 10 days or more—or if they suddenly worsen after a brief improvement (“double sickening”)—that can point to a bacterial infection that may benefit from antibiotics.\n\nSince you’re at day 8 and the symptoms are still progressing, we’re close to that threshold. Rather than starting antibiotics today, I’d recommend we reassess in the next 24–48 hours. In the meantime, you can ease discomfort with:\n\n- Saline nasal rinses or sprays  \n- Warm compresses over your cheeks and forehead  \n- Over-the-counter pain relievers (acetaminophen or ibuprofen, if safe for you)  \n- A topical nasal decongestant spray (like oxymetazoline) for up to 3 days only\n\nIf you develop a fever ≥39 °C or notice a sharp increase in pain or thick, colored discharge, or if you’re still no better by day 10, please reach out right away and we can start an antibiotic. Does that plan feel manageable to you?"
