          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I can see how frustrating it is to keep feeling worse each day. Let me clarify why I’m still advising we wait just a little longer.\n\nCurrent evidence-based guidelines say we should start an antibiotic ONLY when:  \n• symptoms have lasted ≥10 days without ANY improvement, OR  \n• there is “double-sickening” (a clear worsening after an initial partial recovery), OR  \n• there is severe illness from the outset (fever ≥39 °C plus purulent discharge or facial pain for at least 3 straight days).\n\nYou are at 8 days with progressive (not “double-sickening”) symptoms. That still falls short of the threshold shown to benefit from antibiotics, and starting too early exposes you to possible side-effects (diarrhea, rash, yeast infections) without proven benefit. The extra 24–48 hours is actually when the data show we can tell viral from bacterial infection with much higher accuracy.\n\nIf you spike a fever ≥39 °C, develop severe facial swelling or eye pain, or feel dramatically worse overnight, contact me immediately and I’ll prescribe the same day. Otherwise, please continue the comfort measures I listed, and let’s touch base in two days—sooner if anything changes.\n\nI know it’s hard to wait when you’re suffering, but this short pause gives us the safest, most effective path forward."
