          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear how strongly you feel, and I wish I could simply hand you a prescription to give you peace of mind.  However, the evidence is clear that starting antibiotics at day 8 with steadily worsening—but not yet severe—symptoms does not shorten the illness, does not prevent complications, and does expose you to unnecessary side-effects.  \n\nThe safest, most effective point to start treatment is at day 10 (or sooner if you develop fever ≥39 °C with purulent discharge, or marked facial swelling/eye pain).  That cut-off is not arbitrary; it’s based on large studies showing that until then, most people improve on their own.\n\nIf we reach day 10 and you are still not improving—or if you worsen rapidly before then—I will prescribe an antibiotic without delay.  In the meantime, I can call in a prescription for a stronger pain reliever or a short course of oral steroids if the pressure is unbearable, but the antibiotic itself should wait.\n\nI know waiting feels like a risk, but the bigger risk is treating unnecessarily.  Let’s check in tomorrow (day 9) and again the next day.  If the criteria are met at any point, we’ll start antibiotics that same day."
        },
