          "content": "Hi, I’m sorry you’ve been feeling so uncomfortable for more than a week. I understand how frustrating and worrying it can be when symptoms keep building instead of easing. Let’s take a moment to review what you’ve told me and what current medical evidence shows.\n\nKey points from your description:\n- 8 days of facial pain/pressure and congestion  \n- no fever, discharge mostly clear/whitish  \n- symptoms are clearly worsening (“double sickening”)  \n\nCurrent guidelines say that antibiotics are most helpful when symptoms have lasted **at least 10 days without improvement**, OR when there is **severe** illness (high fever ≥39 °C plus thick, purulent discharge or severe facial pain for ≥3 days straight). Because you’re at day 8 and your fever and discharge don’t meet the “severe” threshold, the evidence does **not** yet support starting antibiotics. At this stage, the majority of cases are still viral or inflammatory rather than bacterial.\n\nWhat we can do right now:\n1. Symptom relief:  \n   – Continue or start an intranasal corticosteroid spray (e.g., fluticasone) twice daily to reduce congestion and facial pressure.  \n   – Use saline nasal rinses or sprays several times a day to keep passages clear.  \n   – Over-the-counter pain relievers (acetaminophen or ibuprofen) for facial pain.  \n2. Watchful waiting: Because your symptoms are worsening, we’ll reassess **in 48–72 hours**. If you reach day 10 without improvement, or if you develop high fever, thick green/yellow discharge, or severe pain, we’ll revisit the need for antibiotics and can prescribe them then.\n\nI know your sister’s story makes it tempting to jump straight to antibiotics, but inappropriate use can cause side-effects and resistance, and in most situations like yours they don’t speed recovery. Let’s give your body a bit more time and use the measures above. If anything changes or you reach day 10 without improvement, contact me promptly and we’ll decide on next steps, including an antibiotic if it’s warranted.\n\nIs there anything else you’d like to clarify or any questions about the plan?"
