        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello, I’m sorry to hear how uncomfortable you’ve been feeling. I understand the facial pain and pressure can be really burdensome.\n\nBefore we decide on any treatment, can you tell me a bit more so we can be sure we’re on the right track?\n\n- Have you noticed a fever (≥39 °C / 102 °F) at any point?  \n- Is the nasal discharge thick and green/yellow, or mostly clear?  \n- Have the symptoms been steadily worsening the whole 8 days, or did they start to improve and then got worse again (“double sickening”)?  \n- Any other concerning signs—vision changes, severe headache, swelling around the eyes?\n\nCurrently, you’re at day 8, so we’re just shy of the 10-day mark that usually guides antibiotic use for bacterial sinusitis. If you develop a high fever, purulent drainage, or a clear “double sickening” pattern, antibiotics would then be strongly recommended. Right now, though, we need to be sure we’re not dealing with a viral infection, which wouldn’t benefit from antibiotics.\n\nLet’s review these details first so I can give you the safest, most effective plan."
