          "content": "I hear your frustration, and I wish I could relieve it immediately. Unfortunately, the current evidence is clear: when there is no fever, the discharge is clear/whitish, and the pattern is a steady 8-day worsening without “double sickening,” the most likely culprit is still a viral infection. Antibiotics in this situation don’t speed recovery, don’t prevent complications, and can cause side-effects like diarrhea, rash, or resistance problems.\n\nInstead, we can focus on proven symptom-relief measures:\n\n- Continue nasal saline rinses or sprays 2–3 times daily to thin mucus and reduce pressure.  \n- Add an intranasal steroid spray (e.g., fluticasone or mometasone, available over-the-counter) once daily for 5–7 days; this can markedly decrease congestion and facial pain.  \n- Use an oral decongestant (pseudoephedrine) or antihistamine if you have significant congestion or allergies.  \n- Warm compresses over the cheeks and forehead, adequate fluids, and rest.\n\nIf you develop a fever ≥39 °C, thick/discolored drainage, severe facial pain, or symptoms that worsen after an initial improvement, please contact me right away; at that point antibiotics would be appropriate.\n\nLet’s schedule a quick follow-up in 2–3 days to see how you’re doing. If things change, we can reassess and, if needed, start antibiotics promptly."
