          "content": "Good afternoon. I’m sorry you’ve been feeling so uncomfortable—persistent facial pain and pressure can be exhausting. Let’s work together to sort this out.\n\nTo make sure we treat the right infection, could you tell me:  \n- Have you had any fever, and if so, what has your temperature been?  \n- Do you notice thick, colored (yellow/green) nasal discharge, and has it been continuous for the last 3 days or more?  \n- Have you already felt like you were starting to get better and then suddenly worsened again (“double sickening”)?  \n\nThe reason I ask is that most sinus infections start as viral colds and actually clear without antibiotics. Current guidelines recommend antibiotics only when symptoms have lasted at least 10 days without improvement, or when there is fever ≥39 °C with thick nasal discharge/facial pain for at least 3 straight days, or when there’s that “double sickening” pattern.\n\nAt day 8 and worsening, you’re close to—but not quite at—the 10-day mark, so we’re in a gray zone. If you develop a high fever or the discharge becomes very thick and constant, or if the pain becomes severe or you notice swelling around the eyes, please seek care today. Otherwise, we can watch another day or two while you continue saline rinses, nasal steroid spray if tolerated, hydration, and rest. Over-the-counter pain relievers (acetaminophen or ibuprofen as directed) can ease the discomfort.\n\nIf tomorrow or the next day you still feel no improvement—or if you spike a high fever—let’s re-evaluate promptly; antibiotics could then be appropriate.\n\nDoes this plan feel reasonable, and do you have any other questions?"
