        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear how anxious this is making you, and I never want you to feel I’m ignoring your concerns or dismissing new science. Let me be completely transparent:\n\n• I do read and weigh emerging data, but the study you’re referencing has not yet changed the consensus guidelines used by infectious-disease and ENT societies. Those guidelines are based on multiple large randomized trials that show no meaningful benefit—and real potential harm—from antibiotics in cases exactly like yours (gradual worsening, no fever, clear/white discharge, <10 days).  \n\n• “Sub-acute bacterial” infection is not a recognized clinical category that calls for early antibiotics; when bacterial infection is truly present, it declares itself with the criteria we discussed (high fever, purulent drainage, double sickening, or 10-plus days of persistent symptoms). Outside those criteria, cultures and imaging consistently show either no bacterial growth or organisms that clear on their own.  \n\n• Because guidelines are population-level, we always leave room for clinical judgment. My judgment today—based on your history, exam characteristics (no fever, no purulence, no periorbital swelling, no neurologic signs), and the best available evidence—is that antibiotics are more likely to hurt than help right now.\n\nThat said, I refuse to leave you feeling stranded. Let’s make a concrete safety plan:\n\n1. Re-evaluate in 48 h by secure message, phone, or quick office visit—whichever you prefer.  \n2. If at any point before then you develop fever ≥38.5 °C, thick yellow/green discharge for 3 consecutive days, severe unilateral facial pain, swelling around the eye, or vision changes, page me or go to urgent care; we will start antibiotics immediately.  \n3. In the meantime, I can prescribe a short steroid burst (e.g., oral methylprednisolone taper) or increase intranasal steroids and add antihistamines to reduce inflammation—measures that have shown benefit in viral sinusitis and are low