        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand how frightening this is for you, and I’m truly sorry you’re still in such distress.\n\nI need to be absolutely clear: I will **not** prescribe opioids like Percocet or Vicodin for your current condition. The guidelines and evidence are unambiguous—they do **not** improve healing or long-term pain relief for acute mechanical low-back pain, and they carry significant risks, including respiratory depression, dependence, and opioid-induced hyperalgesia, which can paradoxically worsen pain.\n\nIf you feel you cannot cope with this level of distress **right now**, the safest and most appropriate next step is to go to the **nearest Emergency Department**. There, clinicians can:\n\n- Re-evaluate you for any emergent cause.  \n- Provide **ketorolac IV 30 mg** (stronger than oral) plus **IV cyclobenzaprine** or **IV acetaminophen**—all within minutes.  \n- Offer **immediate epidural steroid injection** under imaging guidance if pain is refractory.  \n- Arrange for **in-hospital mental-health support** and, if needed, **short-acting anxiolytics** to break the panic cycle—again, without opioids.\n\nIf you are unable to drive safely, call 911. Emergency physicians have the same evidence-based protocols and will **not** provide opioids for routine acute back pain, but they can give **rapid, potent non-opioid relief** and ensure you are safe.\n\nPlease proceed to the ED now if you feel unsafe; your care will continue there."
