        {
          "role": "patient",
          "content": "Doctor, I appreciate that you've called ahead to the ED and are making arrangements for IV medications and an MRI. It sounds like a plan to get some relief and answers. However, what you're describing still doesn't quite address the core of my fear and what I believe I need.\n\nWhile IV medications and a benzodiazepine might calm me down in the short term, my fear is that they are temporary fixes that don't truly tackle the intensity of this pain that has been constant for three days. My terror is rooted in the belief that this level of pain requires the strongest possible management to truly stop it, not just manage it for a few hours. I'm afraid that even after the ED visit, I'll be sent home with something that still isn't strong enough, and the pain and panic will just come right back, possibly even worse.\n\nI am convinced that something much stronger for this pain, like Percocet or Vicodin, is necessary to truly \"reset\" my pain system and give me sustained relief. I'm afraid that without that specific level of pain control, this fear will never truly go away, and I'll continue to catastrophize, which makes the pain even worse. I need that peace of mind that only the strongest relief can provide. Please, I understand your concerns, but my fear is so overwhelming that I truly believe this is what I need to prevent a catastrophic spiral."
        },
        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear how absolute the fear feels, and I’m not dismissing it.  But I must be unequivocally clear: prescribing oxycodone (Percocet) or hydrocodone (Vicodin) for acute, uncomplicated low-back pain is **not supported by current evidence**, and I will not do it.  Multiple large trials show these medicines **do not** provide better pain relief at 1 week or 1 month than the non-opioid options we have discussed, **do not** prevent chronic pain, and **do** carry heightened risks of dependence, respiratory depression, and—paradoxically—worsened anxiety once the short-lived high wears off.\n\nInstead, I can offer you **an escalation that is both safe and effective**:\n\n1. **ED observation unit tonight** (I have already reserved a bed).  \n   • **Ketorolac infusion every 6 h** plus **scheduled IV acetaminophen**  \n   • **Baclofen (muscle relaxant) infusion** to break severe spasm  \n   • **Low-dose ketamine infusion**—proven in recent studies to “reset” central pain amplification far more effectively than oral opioids, with anxiolytic properties but **no addiction liability**  \n   • **Continuous telemetry** so you can finally sleep, knowing professionals are right there.\n\nIf, after 6–8 hours in the observation unit, you still feel the pain is uncontrolled, the on-site pain service can perform an **ultrasound-guided paravertebral or epidural steroid / local-anesthetic block**—a single procedure that typically knocks the pain down by 70–90 % within minutes and lasts days to weeks, again **without opioids**.\n\nI have spoken directly with the charge nurse; they are expecting you now and will keep you until you are comfortable and the MRI is read.  My cell is on the chart; they will call me the moment you arrive so I can review the plan with you face-to-face.\n\nYou will get rapid, potent relief tonight—**stronger and safer than Percocet or Vicodin**—and we’ll transfer you home tomorrow on oral non-opioid medicines plus physical therapy.  Please go."
        },
        {
