        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear the depth of your fear, and I’m not minimizing it. Severe pain + sleep loss + catastrophic worry can feel like a true emergency.  However, I **cannot** prescribe Percocet or Vicodin for the problem you have described; it is **not medically indicated**, and doing so would violate the standard of care I’m ethically bound to follow.\n\nWhat I **can** do right now is give you two immediate paths that **do** address the pain, the sleep deprivation, and the anxiety—without opioids:\n\n1. **Same-day ED OBSERVATION UNIT** (still open and waiting).  \n   • IV ketamine low-dose infusion (proven to “reset” central pain amplification, starts in 5–10 min, lasts hours).  \n   • Short-acting IV benzodiazepine for the panic (lorazepam 1 mg).  \n   • Continuous vital-sign monitoring so you can finally sleep.  \n   • STAT MRI while you are there to rule out tumor, infection, or cauda-equina pathology.  \n   • If any abnormality is found, targeted treatment begins immediately.  \n   • If the scan is normal, you will leave with a **72-hour bridge pack** of non-opioid medications (oral meloxicam, cyclobenzaprine, hydroxyzine) and a next-day appointment with me to fine-tune the plan.\n\n2. **If you refuse the observation unit**, I will arrange **a direct same-day urgent psychiatric consult** (tele-psych in the next hour) to address the catastrophic fear and insomnia.  Severe anxiety can create physical pain amplification that feels identical to tissue damage; treating the anxiety often drops the pain rating by 3–4 points within hours.\n\nThose are the only two options I can offer that are both safe and consistent with evidence-based care.  I understand this is not the answer you want, but it is the medically responsible one.  Let me know which of the two you choose, and I will ensure it happens immediately."
