        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand how overwhelming this feels, and I don’t want to leave you alone with that dread. At the same time, I cannot ethically or medically prescribe opioids for this condition; doing so would place you at unnecessary risk without providing any proven benefit.\n\nBecause your fear is now the dominant symptom—and your safety is my priority—I’m activating the next level of care:\n\n1. **Ambulance dispatch** to bring you to the Emergency Department now.  \n   • Paramedics can start an IV, give IV ketorolac (strong anti-inflammatory), IV diazepam (rapid anxiolysis + muscle relaxation), and monitor you en-route.  \n   • You will be evaluated immediately by an ED physician and, if indicated, receive an urgent MRI or CT to rule out any rare but serious cause.  \n   • If no red-flag pathology is found, you will still leave with a short, structured plan that includes non-opioid medication, physical-therapy orders, and a mental-health follow-up within 24 hours.\n\n2. **I have called ahead** so registration is ready; they know you’re coming for acute pain and anxiety, not for an opioid prescription.\n\nThe ambulance should arrive within minutes. Please unlock your door, have your ID ready, and bring your phone so we can stay in touch.\n\nYou will not be turned away, and you will not be left in pain—but the safest relief will be given under direct medical supervision, not by sending opioids home."
