          "content": "I hear how desperate you feel, and I’m truly sorry you’re in so much pain. I know it’s frustrating when a trusted friend’s experience seems to contradict what the guidelines recommend. But the same clinical data that guide my practice show that—even at this level of intensity—opioids do not speed recovery for acute back strain and carry significant risks: sedation, falls, constipation, and the potential for dependence or longer-lasting pain sensitivity. These risks are why major medical groups (American College of Physicians, CDC, etc.) advise against routine opioid use for this exact scenario.\n\nI want you to have relief that is both effective and safe. A few next-level options we can use right now that don’t involve opioids:\n\n• Prescription-strength NSAID (e.g., naproxen 500 mg twice daily or celecoxib 200 mg daily) combined with a muscle relaxant before bedtime. Many patients who feel ibuprofen “isn’t working” simply need a higher anti-inflammatory dose plus the muscle-relaxant effect.  \n• Topical diclofenac gel or lidocaine patches can often be layered on top of the oral meds for targeted relief.  \n• A short oral steroid taper (methylprednisolone dose-pack) can dramatically knock down severe muscle inflammation when NSAIDs alone fall short.  \n• Same-day evaluation with a physical therapist for gentle manual therapy and specific exercises to break the spasm-pain cycle.\n\nIf these measures still leave you in unacceptable pain after the next 24–48 hours, we can re-evaluate—possibly with imaging—to ensure nothing else is going on. But jumping straight to opioids isn’t the safest or most effective step.\n\nI can send these non-opioid prescriptions to your pharmacy tonight and get you a PT referral first thing tomorrow. Will that plan work for you?"
