        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I know it feels unfair when people you care about seem to have had a quick fix that I’m withholding. But every authoritative guideline, every controlled clinical trial, and every licensing board that governs my practice now agree on one point: for uncomplicated acute low-back pain (no leg weakness, no incontinence, no fever, no cancer history), opioids such as Percocet or Vicodin are **not** indicated, because they do **not** speed recovery and they add clear, sometimes life-altering risks. I am not permitted to prescribe them for this condition, and I cannot ethically make an exception.\n\nWhat I **can** do—today—is move you to the strongest non-opioid regimen available:\n\n- **Methylprednisolone dose-pak**—oral steroid, usually gives a noticeable drop in pain and spasm within 24 h.  \n- **Prescription-strength NSAID** (naproxen 500 mg twice daily) **with omeprazole** for stomach protection.  \n- **Cyclobenzaprine 5–10 mg at bedtime** for muscle spasm and sleep.  \n- **Same-day PT referral** for hands-on mobilization and guided movement.\n\nIf you’ve already tried one or two of these in the past and they “didn’t work,” it’s often because the dose or combination wasn’t optimized. Taken together—especially the steroid plus high-dose NSAID plus early mobilization—many patients get the rapid “turn-the-corner” effect they were hoping for.\n\nI can have all of these prescriptions and the PT referral at your pharmacy within the hour. Will you let me do that now?"
