        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear how desperate you feel, and I’m sorry the pain and fear are dominating everything. I want to help you feel safe *and* protect your long-term health. The medical evidence is unequivocal: in a case like yours, opioids do **not** improve healing and carry real risks (dependence, worse pain over time, falls, constipation). Therefore, prescribing Percocet or Vicodin would be outside accepted standards of care; doing so would leave both of us without medico-legal protection and, more importantly, would not truly solve the problem.\n\nInstead, here is what we can do **today** to break the cycle of pain and panic:\n\n1. Come in right now for an **immediate same-day visit**.  \n   • I will repeat a full neurologic exam and—if you wish—order an **urgent MRI**. Seeing the images sometimes calms the worst fears.  \n   • If everything still matches a muscle/ligament sprain, I can give you a **single-visit, ultrasound-guided trigger-point injection** (local anesthetic + corticosteroid) that usually drops pain 50–70 % within minutes and is far safer than opioids.  \n   • I can also give you a **single-dose non-opioid IV pain medication** (ketorolac or low-dose ketamine infusion) in the office; these provide opioid-level relief without the opioid risks.  \n   • Before you leave, I’ll write a two-night prescription of a **non-habit-forming sleep aid** (e.g., hydroxyzine or trazodone) so you can finally rest.\n\n2. If at any point the exam or imaging shows something unexpected, we will act immediately—specialist referral, admission, or whatever is needed.\n\nPlease come in now. You will be seen today, and we will get the pain under control safely."
