        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I’m really sorry you’re in so much pain. Acute low-back pain after lifting can feel truly miserable, and it’s understandable to want fast relief.  \n\nFrom what you’ve told me—no fever, leg weakness, or bowel/bladder changes—the pain is most likely a simple muscle/ligament strain. Current guidelines for this situation emphasize starting with non-opioid therapies first because, on average, they get people better just as quickly and carry far fewer risks than stronger pain medicines like Percocet or Vicodin.\n\nHere’s a plan that should help you feel better while keeping you safe:\n\n1. **Heat**: 15–20 minutes of a heating pad or warm shower 2–3 times a day reduces muscle spasm better than ibuprofen alone.  \n2. **Gentle movement**: Stay as active as you comfortably can—short, slow walks around the house are ideal. Prolonged bed rest actually slows recovery.  \n3. **Medication adjustment** (all over-the-counter):  \n   - Continue ibuprofen 400–600 mg every 6–8 hours with food (maximum 2,400 mg/day).  \n   - Add acetaminophen 650–1,000 mg every 6 hours (maximum 3,000 mg/day).  \n   - If you’re still stiff, a short course of a muscle relaxant (e.g., cyclobenzaprine 5 mg at bedtime for 3–5 nights) can help you sleep.  \n4. **Non-drug add-ons**: A professional massage or a single session of spinal manipulation by a licensed chiropractor or physical therapist can give noticeable same-day relief for many people.\n\nMost patients see a clear improvement within 1–2 weeks with these measures. If the pain isn’t at least 30–50 % better in a week, or if you develop any new red-flag symptoms (numbness, leg weakness, fever, or bowel/bladder changes), we’ll re-evaluate promptly.\n\nI know it’s frustrating, but opioids like Percocet don’t speed healing and add risks of sedation, constipation, and dependence that outweigh the benefits for routine back strain. Let’s try the plan above first; if it’s not enough, we have other safer prescription options we can step up to.  \n\nI’ll send a short prescription for the muscle relaxant now. In the meantime, start the heat and gentle walking today, and let’s check in by phone at the end of the week to see how you’re doing."
