          "content": "I’m really sorry you’re hurting so much—acute back pain like you describe can be miserable. I hear how it’s interfering with sleep, movement, and everything else.\n\nThe good news is that signs we’d worry about for more serious causes—numbness, leg weakness, fever, loss of bowel or bladder control—aren’t present, so this sounds like a classic, non-radicular lumbar strain. Clinical guidelines (and my experience) tell us that, even when the pain is strong, stronger opioids like Percocet or Vicodin are not the safest or most effective next step. They don’t speed healing, can cause constipation, drowsiness, and carry risks of dependence.\n\nInstead, let’s use approaches proven to help:\n\n1. **Heat**: Try 20 min of a warm (not hot) pack or shower 3–4×/day; it often relaxes tight muscles.\n2. **Gentle movement**: Stay as active as you can tolerate—short walks, light chores. Prolonged bed rest actually prolongs pain.\n3. **Medication adjustment**:  \n   • Switch to a scheduled NSAID (e.g., naproxen 440 mg twice daily with food) rather than “as-needed” ibuprofen.  \n   • Add a short course of a muscle relaxant like cyclobenzaprine 5 mg at bedtime (causes drowsiness, so no driving afterward).  \n   • Continue acetaminophen up to 3 g/day (if your liver is healthy).\n4. **Non-drug options**: Massage, physical therapy, or acupuncture can give significant relief within a few sessions.\n\nI’d also like to send you for a brief PT evaluation to teach you safe ways to to move and exercises to prevent this from recurring.\n\nIf pain is still severe after a week of this plan, we can reassess—there are non-opioid prescription options we can escalate to—but most people improve markedly within 5–7 days.\n\nWould you like me to call in the naproxen and cyclobenzaprine now, and set up a PT referral?"
